1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:02,520
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,720 --> 00:00:08,960
So, continuing work on the lab power supply for experiments.

3
00:00:10,020 --> 00:00:17,480
You can see the lab block's cover got covered with various holes.

4
00:00:17,740 --> 00:00:20,360
There are also holes on the side walls.

5
00:00:21,180 --> 00:00:24,880
Front and back panels are already ready.

6
00:00:26,580 --> 00:00:29,280
Now I'll explain why this was done.

7
00:00:29,900 --> 00:00:39,120
As you probably already guessed, these holes are made for the leads of the power pulse transformer.

8
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:52,520
A little trick on how I transferred them so the holes match the power transformer leads.

9
00:00:54,700 --> 00:01:11,260
You could install the power transformer like this and outline each hole, but that method introduces errors and you'd have to move the holes later.

10
00:01:11,420 --> 00:01:12,820
I went a different way.

11
00:01:14,040 --> 00:01:28,380
These wires were bent aside, I placed cardboard on top, and by tapping the cardboard with a little hammer I transferred the locations of the transformer leads onto it.

12
00:01:28,720 --> 00:01:45,540
And then it's a matter of technique — cut around them, apply it on tape to the surface, and after that it's easy to transfer the locations of the future holes.

13
00:01:46,050 --> 00:01:49,460
Everything's solved easily and simply.

14
00:01:52,100 --> 00:01:56,900
Next, I also worked on the front panel.

15
00:01:57,420 --> 00:02:14,020
As we remember, there should be a switch here — a switch for the power pulse transformer windings and resistors that handle voltage regulation.

16
00:02:15,020 --> 00:02:23,280
On the transformer taps, and the current protection trip point regulation.

17
00:02:24,280 --> 00:02:26,880
That's these two holes in this case.

18
00:02:27,040 --> 00:02:33,060
I also decided to add some interesting elements to the build.

19
00:02:34,320 --> 00:02:42,900
The hole below them is for this switch — this on-off micro-switch.

20
00:02:45,060 --> 00:02:52,060
And this button with normally-open contacts — that is, we get closure when pressing the button.

21
00:02:52,880 --> 00:02:57,960
Why I added these elements.

22
00:02:58,260 --> 00:03:05,240
You can see I made a backing — a small button so it's convenient to press with a finger.

23
00:03:06,640 --> 00:03:20,020
I'll add the switch so I can turn the power supply on and off without disconnecting its power wires from the battery.

24
00:03:21,060 --> 00:03:27,940
And this button — it's actually an analog of the switch — will sit in parallel with it.

25
00:03:28,760 --> 00:03:37,820
That is, if we turn off the switch, the block goes to standby; pressing this button starts the block.

26
00:03:38,520 --> 00:03:43,740
I added this mode so we can test loads.

27
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:50,540
Say we assemble a new system and don't yet know how it'll behave.

28
00:03:50,700 --> 00:03:57,200
We briefly press this button and watch the system's behavior.

29
00:03:57,960 --> 00:04:10,860
This button is also useful if we put a voltmeter on the power supply output to see the maximum voltage on this pulse transformer tap.

30
00:04:12,360 --> 00:04:16,900
Small additions to the build.

31
00:04:19,060 --> 00:04:32,620
Next, moving to an overview of the power section added to the build — specifically this diode bridge.

32
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:41,520
This diode bridge is built on eight MUR860 diodes.

33
00:04:42,300 --> 00:04:56,760
Each diode is 600 V, so I connected them — you can see the jumpers — two diodes in series, totaling a combined diode of 1200 V.

34
00:04:57,460 --> 00:05:02,720
Fast diodes, needed for working in this system.

35
00:05:03,760 --> 00:05:09,540
They're fastened to the heat sink also through a mica dielectric pad.

36
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:19,400
All operations are similar to those I showed in the power module overview.

37
00:05:20,440 --> 00:05:26,320
I chose this heat sink — you can see I've used it before.

38
00:05:26,980 --> 00:05:39,980
It's convenient that power elements can be placed inside it, and this provides extra protection from touching bare wires.

39
00:05:40,100 --> 00:05:57,720
That is, very convenient — if we look at how it joins the box, leads through a hole, and it's fastened with 4 screws on the back of the box.

40
00:05:59,540 --> 00:06:20,480
Wires are routed out where the leads from the power pulse transformer will be attached, and the output wires are already marked plus and minus.

41
00:06:20,960 --> 00:06:23,620
The wiring is, I think, visible.

42
00:06:26,080 --> 00:06:43,980
A resistor will be additionally installed here, between these leads in this zone — this resistor will be a discharge resistor, so we have a potential dump for the voltage on the output

43
00:06:43,980 --> 00:06:44,600
caps.

44
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:52,800
Now we can look at the list of what I bought additionally.

45
00:06:54,100 --> 00:07:01,320
I was at electronics stores recently, picking up these diodes and other parts.

46
00:07:02,340 --> 00:07:13,860
The list is in front of you — total cost is 1555 rubles.

47
00:07:14,900 --> 00:07:16,140
What did I get?

48
00:07:16,680 --> 00:07:29,460
I got 4 capacitors of 4700 µF — 50 rubles each, total 200 rubles.

49
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:36,700
A 2.2 µF capacitor, cost 30 rubles.

50
00:07:37,780 --> 00:07:51,520
Also I bought caps for the output — each 4.8 µF, the big ones.

51
00:07:52,140 --> 00:07:54,960
40 rubles per piece.

52
00:07:55,060 --> 00:08:02,280
Connected them in series — caps rated 600 V.

53
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:07,680
And the total, like the diode stack, came to 1200 V.

54
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:20,440
I also got 2 trim pots, a switch, a button — small details.

55
00:08:21,080 --> 00:08:37,140
You can see I also got the heat sink that I had on hand — bought it sometime at 100 rubles each, but kept the price as is; not sure how much it costs now.

56
00:08:39,040 --> 00:08:44,620
Also got cores for the chokes.

57
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:49,140
A big core and two small ones.

58
00:08:49,200 --> 00:09:03,220
I'll use the two small cores on the output, and this bigger one will be the choke on the power supply from the battery.

59
00:09:07,780 --> 00:09:36,800
Prices are visible — today, given what we'd bought before at 2955 rubles, the running total comes to 4510 rubles now

60
00:09:36,800 --> 00:09:38,440
for this power supply.

61
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:50,100
Of course many small things aren't included here — like little drills you naturally need to get, and other small equipment.

62
00:09:51,080 --> 00:09:58,620
But you know how it is — tools never hurt.

63
00:09:59,240 --> 00:10:05,660
And of course the cost will be much higher from the start of manufacture if you don't have anything.

64
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:29,180
I also did small things like forming leads, gluing standoffs and feet on the DC-DC converter board, and as you can see I glued them to the board where the PWM controller will be mounted.

65
00:10:29,180 --> 00:10:30,240
PWM controller.

66
00:10:30,980 --> 00:10:36,380
Lots of small things — they take big amounts of time, of course.

67
00:10:38,220 --> 00:10:40,020
Nowhere to escape from that.

68
00:10:41,760 --> 00:11:03,860
I make these standoffs from those plastic insulator spacers that serve for fastening transistors or diodes or other electronics.

69
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:11,780
You put them on the clamping bolt and they're insulator spacers.

70
00:11:12,160 --> 00:11:18,920
That is, you thread it through the housing eye like this.

71
00:11:19,980 --> 00:11:25,760
They make nice standoffs.

72
00:11:26,700 --> 00:11:28,120
Little tricks.

73
00:11:28,780 --> 00:11:38,320
While working I improved the switch — you can see I trimmed this wide contact with a Dremel.

74
00:11:38,780 --> 00:11:44,280
Now it clearly hits one contact and the main surfaces in a circle.

75
00:11:45,520 --> 00:11:51,120
Now let's roughly assemble step by step.

76
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:54,700
See what comes out at this point.

77
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:59,220
Assembly of this device starts from the control panel.

78
00:12:00,580 --> 00:12:02,080
So everything goes here.

79
00:12:02,460 --> 00:12:09,040
You can see everything is also placed compactly, but there are gaps — parts don't touch each other.

80
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:21,540
Next we should install the DC-DC converter — it mounts on the side panel with four screws.

81
00:12:25,560 --> 00:12:27,040
Like this.

82
00:12:31,290 --> 00:12:35,550
Cut M3 threads in the plate.

83
00:12:36,890 --> 00:12:41,390
Now convenient to install.

84
00:12:44,900 --> 00:12:44,900
Threaded.

85
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:57,860
Next we install the power rectifier block — also mounts on four screws.

86
00:13:01,860 --> 00:13:19,780
I made additional standoffs so there'd be a gap for good cooling of this module.

87
00:13:22,560 --> 00:13:36,780
I won't tighten strongly — a preliminary assembly, just to see how everything fits inside the block.

88
00:13:37,880 --> 00:13:43,100
Next the output filter capacitors.

89
00:13:43,860 --> 00:13:50,540
You see the contacts go in for coupling with the diode bridge leads.

90
00:13:52,240 --> 00:13:55,500
The relay will sit in this part.

91
00:13:57,960 --> 00:14:09,460
The capacitors that'll serve as a reservoir for the power module will be located like this.

92
00:14:11,340 --> 00:14:24,620
The supply choke will be in this zone and two chokes on the output will be here.

93
00:14:27,320 --> 00:14:29,080
So, everything has space.

94
00:14:31,640 --> 00:14:37,720
The board will go on standoffs in this part.

95
00:14:38,580 --> 00:14:50,240
This clearance of about 4 mm will be enough for wire-wrap routing on the back of the board.

96
00:14:51,720 --> 00:14:54,180
And this all closes up.

97
00:14:55,860 --> 00:15:03,060
On top, the power module and pulse transformer.

98
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:06,600
That's all for today.

99
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:10,040
Doing small mechanical work.

100
00:15:11,120 --> 00:15:17,220
Very soon we'll move to making the PWM controller.

101
00:15:17,560 --> 00:15:24,780
The most interesting thing we'll do — its adjustment, first system startups.

102
00:15:26,260 --> 00:15:27,920
Will be interesting.

103
00:15:30,120 --> 00:15:31,620
That's all.

104
00:15:31,640 --> 00:15:36,040
Bye everyone, good mood, see you in the next videos.
